# iOS Port Prototype

The current iOS port prototype is built in 2 parts. The core libraries such as
XUL are built as-normal, and then an xcode project is used to bundle these
libraries into an iOS application, which can be deployed to a device or
simulator.

Currently there is no support for running automated iOS tests, though this is
being investigated.

## Simulator

### Building

1. Update your .mozconfig as described below:

```
# Enable the iOS application target.
ac_add_options --enable-application=mobile/ios

# Specify the relevant target for the iOS simulator.
# Note that runninng on an iOS device is more complex, see below.
ac_add_options --target=aarch64-apple-ios-sim  # simulator (apple silicon)
```

2. Build the main core of XUL with `./mach build` as normal.

### Running

Currently the in-tree wrapper for Gecko on iOS is the minimal "TestRunner"
application. This can be run in one of the following ways:

1. If you have a simulator open or a device configured, you can use the
   `./mach run` command to install `TestRunner` on the simulator, and launch
   it. Note that to use `./mach run` with a real device, you will need to have
   `ios-deploy` installed, and your signing team configured through the xcode
   project.

2. You can open the xcode project at
   `mobile/ios/TestRunner/TestRunner.xcodeproj`, and run it from there.

## Real Device

### Building

To build for a real device, you'll need to provide some extra options in the
`.mozconfig`:

```
# The target for a real iOS device is different than the simulator. This should
# replace `--target=aarch64-apple-ios-sim`.
ac_add_options --target=aarch64-apple-ios

# Due to the iOS sandboxing restrictions it is not possible to run the JS JIT
# on iOS, meaning it has to be disabled.
ac_add_options --disable-jit

# There are also failures attempting to initialize out RLBox WASM sandbox
# currently, so that feature also needs to be disabled to run on-device.
ac_add_options --without-wasm-sandboxed-libraries
```

In addition, e10s will be forcibly disabled when running on a real device, as
child process launching is blocked by the iOS sandbox. Any logic which tries to
launch a child process on device will fail.

You are likely to run into a signing issue when trying to build, as the "team"
on the project is my apple developer account. You'll need to modify the signing
team in xcode to your own apple developer account to get the signing to work,
and then approve that developer through the phone's settings interface.

### Running

Running on a device is similar to the simulator section, however you will need
to have the `ios-deploy` tool installed to use `./mach run` with a real device.
